 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/utudamorf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tudamorf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/8/01 8:14:01 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.geocities.com/lag999/rtfm.txt width=100 height=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Alt-tab (background) functionality restored</span><hr size=1> EQAquinas says:  <b><i>Do you feel the same way about your obligations to Mythic? If you cancel your account without a good reason, would they be justified in suing you for bad faith?</b></i><br>
<br>
The issue isn't whether you have a "good reason", but rather whether you are doing it for a "bad" reason.  Terminating users who are just using features of their OS (not in violation of the agreement) would be a "bad" reason in this case.<br>
<br>
As for the user, given the nature of the subscription, it's rather hard for them to cancel in bad faith.  I suppose if someone found an exploit that allows them to get more than one free month, and they cancel on the 30th day to prevent detection, that would be bad faith.  But usually, it will be because they don't like the game any more, which is as valid a reason as any. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/9/01 5:48:49 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Alt-tab (background) functionality restored</span><hr size=1> Technically, it's the "covenant of good faith and fair dealing," and it's implied by law in all contracts.  In essence, it means that each party to the contract will act in good faith in order to not frustrate the contractual expectations of the other parties.<br>
<br>
In contracts where one party has "sole discretion" to do something, or the right to take unilateral action, this is usually interpreted to mean that the party with that discretion will exercise its discretion in good faith.  "Sole discretion" is usually determined to just identify which party it is that is expected to act in such a manner; it doesn't relieve them of the obligation to act in good faith. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ulilwolf.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LilWolf</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/9/01 8:29:59 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> My main question</span><hr size=1> If I use a program so I can get work done on my downtime, or start another CD is Mystic going to come looking for me?<br>
