 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f5e6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ueqaquinas.showPublicProfile?language=EN>EQAquinas</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/9/01 8:40:34 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Alt-tab (background) functionality restored</span><hr size=1> <b>Technically, it's the "covenant of good faith and fair dealing," and it's implied by law in all contracts.</b><br>
<br>
It’s really not that universal.  It appears that Virginia, for instance, where Mythic is located and whose law governs the EULA, does not recognize such an implied covenant in ordinary contracts.<br>
<br>
And even if it did, good faith is actually a pretty low standard of conduct.  A “bad reason,” as someone put it, really isn’t enough – “bad motive” would be closer.  You can be dead wrong and still act in good faith.  You can be objectively unreasonable and still act in good faith.  As long as Mythic sincerely believes that they’re acting for the good of the game, they’re probably in the clear as far as “good faith” goes.  Disproving that would be an awfully tough task, unless you’ve got some peculiar circumstances (e.g., Mythic employees have a personal grudge against you).<br>
<br>
<b>As for the user, given the nature of the subscription, it's rather hard for them to cancel in bad faith. ... But usually, it will be because they don't like the game any more, which is as valid a reason as any.</b><br>
<br>
So do you think that Mythic has a valid reason for cancelling your account if they just don't like selling you the game any more?<br>
<br>
It seems to me that you're using a double standard for this "good faith" obligation.  When discussing Mythic's actions, you suggest that they have a "bad reason" for canceling if the user is "not in violation of the agreement."  But when discussing the users, you say that they can cancel just because "they don't like the game any more," which has nothing to do with whether Mythic has violated the agreement.<br>
<br>
Can one party cancel the agreement in good faith even if the other party hasn't violated it?  If so, why can't Mythic cancel for use of a minimizing utility (even if it doesn't violate the agreement)?  If not, why can the user terminate in good faith just because he doesn't like the game any more?<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#e6ebd7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uscirocco.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Scirocco</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FAQ/Index Moderator</span><br> <font color=#333399>(11/9/01 10:04:35 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Alt-tab (background) functionality restored</span><hr size=1> <b>btw, they have full rights to drop everyones account if they want. So whether this is legal or not doesn't make a difference. </b><br>
<br>
Point being that they don't necessarily have full rights to drop everyone's account if they want.  They are still bound by the covenant of good faith and fair dealing.<br>
<br>
With regard to Virginia law, two points.  First, you are presuming that Virginia law will apply.  That may not be the case, since the sale of the game actually took place in many states.  And I don't know about you, but there's no-click-through-EULA when I start DAoC (and even if there were, the validity of such clickwrap licenses remains questionable in consumer transactions).<br>
<br>
Second, Virginia law does appear to be unsettled on this point.  Several cases do say that there is no implied covenant where there are binding and valid contractual rights expressly created, but others say something along the following lines:<br>
<br>
<i> While this contract does not fall within the scope of the Uniform Commercial <br>
Code in effect in Virginia, that code does legislatively impose a duty of good<br>
faith on the performance of all contracts falling under the U.C.C.  <=73> <br>
Virginia Code @ 8.1-203. One circuit court in Virginia has stated broadly that<br>
every contract contains an implied duty of good faith in its performance. <br>
 <=74>  Stepp v. Outdoor World Corp., 18 Va. Cir. 106, 111 (1989) (real estate<br>
 contract) . Michie's Jurisprudence uses similar broad language:  <=210>  "The<br>
law implies a  covenant of good faith  . . . in every  contract  . . . ." 4B<br>
M.J.,  Contracts,  20 (Cum. Supp. 1993). This is consistent with the Restatement<br>
(Second) of Contracts @ 205 (1981), which states the majority opinion in courts <br>
nationwide. In addition, the legislature in Virginia in essence has mandated<br>
that an insurance company act toward its insured in good faith.  <=75>  Va. Code<br>
@ 38.2-510(6). Provisions of the insurance sections of the Virginia Code have<br>
often been ruled to be implied conditions of an insurance contract by the<br>
Virginia Supreme Court. See, e.g.,  <=76>  State Farm v. Duncan, 203 Va. 440,<br>
125 S.E.2d 154 (1962). The Fourth Circuit found that the responsibility set out <br>
in  <=77>  Virginia Code[**31] @ 38.1-52.9(6) (now @ 38.2-510(6)), parallels an <br>
insurer's contractual duty of good faith.   <=78>  A & E, supra, 798 F.2d at<br>
676.<br>
<br>
   Based on much of the authority cited above, the Fourth Circuit opined that<br>
the Virginia Supreme Court would imply such a duty of good faith on [*568] all<br>
contracting parties in performing duties under an agreement.   <=79>  A & E<br>
Supply Co., supra, 798 F.2d at 676.  <=211>  Bad faith conduct gives rise to a<br>
contract action, not a tort suit, as the duty arises from and extends only to<br>
the agreement itself.   <=80>  Id. at 676.</i><br>
<br>
<br>
An interesting legal issue...at least for the Virginia lawyers.<br>
